1 to secure a rental that is commensurate with other rentals of similar timeshares
2 or use rights generally secured at that time.
3 (d) For timeshare estates located in this State, the managing entity shall have a lien on a
4 timeshare for any assessment levied against that timeshare from the date such assessment
5 becomes due. The managing entity shall also have a lien on a timeshare estate of any owner for
6 the cost of any maintenance, repairs, or replacement resulting from an act of the owner or the
7 owner's guest or lessee that results in damage to the timeshare property. All of the following
8 apply to a lien imposed under this section:
9 (1) The managing entity, or the holder of the lien, may bring a judicial action in
10 its name to foreclose the lien in the nature of an action to foreclose a mortgage
11 or deed of trust and may also bring an action to recover a money judgment for
12 the unpaid assessments without waiving any claim of lien. As an alternative
13 to initiating a judicial action, the managing entity entity, or the holder of the
14 lien, may initiate a nonjudicial timeshare trustee foreclosure proceeding
15 pursuant to G.S. 93A-62.1 to foreclose the assessment lien.
16 (2) The lien is effective from the date of and shall relate back to the recording of
17 the original timeshare declaration, or, in the case of lien on a timeshare located
18 in a phase timeshare program, the last to occur of the recording of the original
19 timeshare declaration or amendment creating the timeshare. However, as to
20 first mortgages of record, the lien is effective from and after filing of the claim
21 of lien in the office of the clerk of superior court in the county where the
22 timeshare estate is located.
23 (3) The claim of lien shall state the name of the timeshare program and identify
24 the timeshare for which the lien is effective, state the name of the owner, state
25 the assessment amount due, and state the due dates. The claim of lien shall be
26 signed and acknowledged by an officer or agent of the managing entity or the
27 holder.holder of the lien. The claim of lien shall contain the following
28 statement in print that is in boldface, capital letters, and no smaller than the
29 largest print used elsewhere in the document:
30 "THIS DOCUMENT CONSTITUTES A LIEN AGAINST YOUR PROPERTY, AND IF
31 THE LIEN IS NOT PAID, THE ASSOCIATION MAY PROCEED WITH FORECLOSURE
32 AGAINST YOUR TIMESHARE IN THE NATURE OF AN ACTION TO FORECLOSE A
33 MORTGAGE OR DEED OF TRUST OR A TIMESHARE TRUSTEE FORECLOSURE
34 UNDER NORTH CAROLINA LAW."
35 (4) The lien shall expire upon the earlier of:
36 a. The date it is satisfied.
37 b. Five years from the date the claim of lien is filed unless an action to
38 enforce or foreclose the lien is commenced within that time.
39 (5) A claim of lien for assessments may include assessments which are due when
40 the claim is recorded and all assessments that subsequently become due and
41 are delinquent. Upon full payment, the person making the payment is entitled
42 to receive a satisfaction of the lien.
43 (6) A judgment in any judicial action or suit brought to foreclose the claim of lien
44 may include costs and reasonable attorney's fees for the substantially
45 prevailing party. For a timeshare trustee foreclosure brought pursuant to this
46 section, the managing entity or the holder of the lien shall be entitled to
47 recover its costs, including reasonable attorney's fees and trustee's fees.
48 (e) A Except in the event of a timeshare trustee foreclosure conducted in accordance with
49 G.S. 93A-62.1, a successor in interest, regardless of how the timeshare has been acquired,
50 including a purchaser at a judicial sale or foreclosure trustee sale, is jointly and severally liable
51 with their predecessor in interest for all unpaid assessments against the predecessor up to the time
